        "content": "     1→[\n     2→  {\n     3→    \"title\": \"Meet The $9 Billion AI Company Reimagining Vibe Coding\",\n     4→    \"description\": \"Forbes profile of Replit CEO Amjad Masad and the launch of Agent 4. Replit raised $400M at $9B valuation (up from $3B six months ago). Agent 4 introduces a digital canvas for vibe coding where users can tweak mockups, app designs, and collaborate in real-time. Focuses on non-technical workers like sales, marketing, and small business owners. Customers include Zillow (600 seats, 7,000+ apps built), Databricks, PayPal, Adobe. Competes with Claude Code ($2.5B annualized revenue) and Cursor ($2B+ annualized revenue). Masad: 'We can't cure cancer. Replit is about making everyone a software engineer.'\",\n     5→    \"author\": \"Richard Nieva (Forbes)\",\n     6→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n     7→    \"url\": \"https://www.forbes.com/sites/richardnieva/2026/03/11/meet-the-9-billion-ai-company-reimagining-vibe-coding-replit-amjad-masad/\",\n     8→    \"published_date\": \"2026-03-11\",\n     9→    \"topics\": [\"vibe coding\", \"Agent 4\", \"Replit\", \"AI agents\", \"non-technical developers\", \"startup funding\"],\n    10→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    11→  },\n    12→  {\n    13→    \"title\": \"Perhaps not Boring Technology after all\",\n    14→    \"description\": \"Simon Willison explores concerns that LLMs for programming would push technology choices towards tools best represented in training data. However, with latest models in good coding agent harnesses, he finds excellent results even with brand new or private tools. Agents can consume documentation and learn patterns from existing codebases, making them effective regardless of technology choices. Also discusses Skills mechanism and projects releasing official skills for agents (Remotion, Supabase, Vercel, Prisma).\",\n    15→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison\",\n    16→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n    17→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/2026/Mar/9/not-so-boring/\",\n    18→    \"published_date\": \"2026-03-09\",\n    19→    \"topics\": [\"LLM\", \"coding agents\", \"technology choices\", \"boring technology\", \"skills mechanism\"],\n    20→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    21→  },\n    22→  {\n    23→    \"title\": \"AI should help us produce better code\",\n    24→    \"description\": \"Simon Willison addresses concerns that outsourcing code to AI tools will result in quality drops. Argues that shipping worse code with agents is a choice - we can choose to ship better code instead. Discusses how to identify which aspects of process hurt quality and fix them when adopting coding agents.\",\n    25→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison\",\n    26→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n    27→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/2026/Mar/10/\",\n    28→    \"published_date\": \"2026-03-10\",\n    29→    \"topics\": [\"AI\", \"coding agents\", \"code quality\", \"agentic engineering\"],\n    30→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    31→  },\n    32→  {\n    33→    \"title\": \"Can coding agents relicense open source through a 'clean room' implementation?\",\n    34→    \"description\": \"Simon Willison discusses how coding agents are extraordinarily good at building 'clean room' implementations of code. Also covers GPT-5.4 and GPT-5.4-pro announcement with August 2025 knowledge cutoff, 1M token context, improvements in spreadsheet/document creation, and benchmark performance.\",\n    35→    \"author\": \"Simon Willison\",\n    36→    \"source\": \"Blog\",\n    37→    \"url\": \"https://simonwillison.net/2026/Mar/5/\",\n    38→    \"published_date\": \"2026-03-05\",\n    39→    \"topics\": [\"coding agents\", \"open source\", \"licensing\", \"clean room implementation\", \"GPT-5.4\"],\n    40→    \"type\": \"discussion\"\n    41→  }\n    42→]\n    43→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"
